# gpsim command script: drive the PIC10F320 footswitch and snapshot PORTA/LATA.
#
# WHAT THIS IS
#   A register-level functional check of the firmware (bypass_mcu_pic10f320.c)
#   running inside gpsim. The debounce algorithm is already covered by the
#   host/formal suite (against the vendored model) and by the firmware<->model
#   equivalence test; this drives the REAL built HEX in gpsim to additionally
#   exercise what those host harnesses mock -- the oscillator/TMR2 tick, the
#   footswitch read on RA3, the debounce integrate/step wiring, and the GPIO
#   outputs -- and asserts the observable register state at four settled
#   checkpoints. The wrapper test/pic/run_gpsim_test.sh parses the snapshots and
#   turns them into PASS/FAIL.
#
# HOW IT IS RUN (see the wrapper / `make test-gpsim`)
#   gpsim -i -pp10f320 <variant>.hex -c test/pic/footswitch_toggle.stc
#   The HEX (any of the five output variants) is supplied on the gpsim command
#   line, so this script is variant-agnostic (the wrapper supplies the per-variant
#   expected LATA). gpsim names the PIC pins ra0..ra3.
#
# PINS (per bypass_mcu_pic10f320.c)
#   RA3 = footswitch (input; high = released, low = pressed)
#   RA0 = status LED  (LATA bit 0; high = effect ENGAGED, low = BYPASS)
#   RA1/RA2 = the active variant's control output(s)
#
# TIMING
#   FOSC = 2 MHz -> instruction clock FOSC/4 = 500 kHz -> 500 cycles per 1 ms.
#   The debounce needs PRESSED_THRESH(8) low samples to register a press and
#   RELEASE_THRESH(25) high samples to re-arm; the relay/mute drivers also block
#   ~12 ms per actuation. All checkpoints below are placed well clear of those
#   windows so every variant has SETTLED by the time it is sampled.
#
# SCENARIO (two MOMENTARY presses; the effect latches between them)
#   cyc      0..12.5k : released  -> BYPASS (power-on default)
#   cyc 12.5k..27.5k  : press #1  (~30 ms)  -> toggles to ENGAGED, then released
#   cyc 27.5k..65k    : released, effect stays ENGAGED (latching)
#   cyc 65k..80k      : press #2  (~30 ms)  -> toggles back to BYPASS
#
# CHECKPOINTS (the wrapper keys on these exact === labels ===)
#   INIT_BYPASS  @ 11.25k : LATA bit0 == 0 (LED off), PORTA bit3 == 1 (released)
#   PRESS1_EARLY @ 14.25k : LATA bit0 == 0 (LED still OFF), PORTA bit3 == 0 (pressed).
#                         This is ~1.75k cyc (~3.5 ms) AFTER the press edge (12.5k) but
#                         ~1.75k cyc BEFORE the earliest legitimate toggle (~16k =
#                         12.5k + PRESSED_THRESH*500). It pins that the TICK GATES the
#                         loop: the debounce demands 8 *separated* 1 ms samples, so a
#                         correct firmware is still mid-debounce here. A firmware
#                         whose tick stopped gating (e.g. the TMR2IF poll never
#                         re-blocks) free-runs and crosses PRESSED_THRESH within
#                         microseconds of the edge -> LED already ON here -> FAIL.
#                         (One-sided *too-fast* guard, run in gpsim's own timer; the
#                         absolute 1 ms period is a bench-only matter -- see test
#                         README "Known gaps".) This is the ONE behaviour the host
#                         harnesses cannot see (they force TMR2IF=1, so the poll never
#                         waits); see the tick-gating mutant in test/run_mutation_tests.sh.
#   PRESS1_LOW   @ 18.75k : PORTA bit3 == 0 (pressed), LATA bit0 == 1 (LED latched
#                         ENGAGED -- the effect toggled ON the press, not release)
#   ENGAGED      @ 37.5k : LATA bit0 == 1 (LED on, latched), PORTA bit3 == 1
#   BYPASS_AGAIN @ 100k : LATA bit0 == 0 (toggled back off)

stimulus asynchronous_stimulus
  initial_state 1
  { 12500, 0,
    27500, 1,
    65000, 0,
    80000, 1 }
  name fsw
end

node n1
attach n1 fsw ra3

break c 11250
run
echo ===INIT_BYPASS===
porta
lata

break c 14250
run
echo ===PRESS1_EARLY===
porta
lata

break c 18750
run
echo ===PRESS1_LOW===
porta
lata

break c 37500
run
echo ===ENGAGED===
porta
lata

break c 100000
run
echo ===BYPASS_AGAIN===
porta
lata

quit
